NumPy - Reshaping Arrays & Array Creation
1. Why Reshape?
Reshaping changes the dimensions of an array without changing its data. It is heavily used in Machine Learning, Deep Learning and Computer Vision.

Example:
arr=np.arange(1,7)
arr.reshape(2,3)
Output:
[[1 2 3]
 [4 5 6]]
2. reshape()
Syntax: array.reshape(rows, columns)

Rules:
• Total number of elements must remain the same.
• Valid: 12 elements -> (3,4), (2,6), (6,2).
• Invalid shapes raise an error.
3. reshape(-1)
NumPy automatically calculates the missing dimension.
Example:
arr.reshape(2,-1)
arr.reshape(-1,4)
4. flatten()
Converts a multi-dimensional array into a 1D array.
Returns a COPY.
5. ravel()
Similar to flatten(), but usually returns a VIEW instead of a copy.
6. transpose()
Rows become columns and columns become rows.
Use A.T or A.transpose().
7. Creating Arrays
np.zeros((2,3)) -> all zeros
np.ones((3,2)) -> all ones
np.eye(3) -> identity matrix
8. arange()
Creates numbers in a range.
Example: np.arange(10,51)
Last value is excluded.
9. linspace()
Creates evenly spaced numbers.
Example: np.linspace(0,1,6)
Difference:
arange() -> step based
linspace() -> number of values based.
10. Random Numbers
np.random.rand(3) -> random decimals
np.random.randint(1,101,10) -> 10 random integers
11. Common Mistakes
❌ reshape(5,3) on 12 elements.
✔ reshape(3,4)

❌ Confusing transpose with reverse.

❌ Using rand() when integers are required.
12. Interview Questions
1. What is reshape()?
2. Difference between flatten() and ravel()?
